  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Purchase for Progress 2014</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">ACF will continue to work with the 2,181 farmers organized into 62 groups targeted in the previous of the project. They plan to increase small holder farmer&#x2019;s income by improving their capacity to participate in market oriented agriculture through utilization of the SCPs for bulking and collective marketing. This will be done through improving access, financial services (through VSLA), improving access to market information and its dissemination, increasing marketable output (through training in post harvest handling and warehouse management), training in farming as a business, encouraging coordinated production, supporting the farmers to implement their business plans, fostering market linkages, direct intervention on the transport constraint, increasing participation of women and providing the farmers with knowledge, equipment and facilities to carry out these activities.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Smallholder Farmers</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The proposed action will continue to work with the 5 Farmer Organizations comprising 2,181 farmers in order to: build on project achievements to-date and maximize utilization of the SCPS for full bulking and collective selling activities through strengthening of planning and organizational capacity of farmer groups. Outputs under the proposed action will be achieved by facilitating planning and institutional capacity building, providing new PHH technologies and further training in Post Harvest Handling (PHH), Farming as Business, and VSLA establishment and linkage to financial institutions. This action will also address the gender gaps among farmer organizations through gender empowerment.</narrative>
  </description>
